Another idea: "Contested squares".
Squares that are reachable by both colors in 1 ply?
But pieces move alternately.
Reachable by Black in 1 ply vs White in 1 ply.
Count squares reachable by Black but not White, and vice versa.
This captures "exclusive mobility".
This is a new feature family.
It requires computing 1-ply reachability for both sides.
This is feasible with bitboards.
For each piece, generate all squares it can move to (sliding until blocked).
Combine for all pieces of a side.
Then compute intersection/difference.
This gives:
- Black exclusive squares
- White exclusive squares
- Contested squares (reachable by both)
This is richer than just total mobility.
It captures "who controls which areas".
This seems promising and not explicitly in top-K (top-K had "influence", but influence might be different).
"Influence" often means control over squares, but "exclusive mobility" is more precise for scoring.
Scoring comes from moves. If you can move to a square that the opponent cannot, you have a safe move.
If a square is contested, moving there might block the opponent or be blocked by them.
This feature family: "Exclusive vs Contested Mobility Squares".

