HARD RULE — the new mapping must include AT LEAST ONE feature family that is ABSENT from every top-K description above. The neural net can already learn sums/diffs/ratios/max/min of features the top-K already expose; pre-computing such aggregations adds no signal. You must add a genuinely new SOURCE of signal, not a rearrangement.

Families worth considering (pick ones NOT in the top-K):
- Parity / ply-counted features (whose turn × contested squares).
- The contested BORDER between black- and white-influenced regions
  — width, length, or squares reachable in equal ply by both.
- Trapped-piece detection (piece whose only escapes shrink in k plies).
- Symmetry signals (how the position changes under board flip /
  colour swap — asymmetry magnitude is informative).
- Distance-to-opponent, or sum of min-Chebyshev distances between
  opposing pieces.
- Moves that would IMMEDIATELY reduce the opponent's mobility
  (origin-square blocking effects, one ply lookahead).
- Discriminants for the specific misclassifications above —
  identify a feature that is cleanly different on those cases.

